President Obama released a statement expressing his condolences on the passing of B.B. King, referring to him as the king of blues and a legend. He highlighted King's humble beginnings as a sharecropper's son in Mississippi and his rise to become a renowned musician and ambassador for American music. The President praised King's hard work, his influence on up-and-coming artists, and his efforts to spread the gospel of the blues. Obama also shared a personal anecdote about singing with King at a blues concert held at the White House. He concluded by saying that while B.B. King may be gone, his music will always have a lasting impact, and there will be a memorable blues session in heaven tonight.